<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="1094" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[163,1070,1020,1276]" pageId="1" pageNumber="1094">
C o m m e n t: 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="EPPELSHEIM" baseAuthorityYear="1878" box="[334,509,1020,1041]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geostiba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="1094" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="armata">
<emphasis box="[334,509,1020,1041]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="1094">Geostiba armata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is by far the most widespread representative of the subgenus in 
<collectingCountry box="[293,367,1049,1070]" name="Greece" pageId="1" pageNumber="1094">Greece</collectingCountry>
, its previously known distribution ranging from the northern Pindos southeastwards to Kato Olympos and Oros Ossa, 
<collectingRegion box="[736,835,1078,1100]" country="Greece" name="Thessalia" pageId="1" pageNumber="1094">Thessalía</collectingRegion>
. The above material represents the first record from Oros Óthris and Fthióida. It is distinguished from other propulations by darker average coloration, an on average broader body, coarser punctation of the male elytra, an on average larger spine on the male tergite VII, and a slightly larger (more dagger-shaped) cristal process of the aedeagus. However, I have been unable to find any discrete differences suggesting that the population from Oros Óthris should represent a distinct species.
</paragraph>
